<h2 class="pageTitle"><span>Summer Research Opportunities</span></h2>

</div>
<div class="contentMain">


<div id="pageContent"><p>The Computer Science Department at Carleton College is committed to providing undergraduate students with research opportunities. The majority of our research opportunities take place over the summer, and are paid positions. The standard stipend for 2011 is $4300 for ten weeks of full-time research.</p>
<p><strong><a title="Summer 2011 Research Projects" href="//apps.carleton.edu/curricular/cs/summerresearch/2011/">Projects for Summer 2011</a><br /></strong></p>
<p>Students can apply for a position in one of three ways:</p>
<p>1.&nbsp; Apply to be a Clare Boothe Luce Scholar (deadline: February 1).&nbsp; See below for details.</p>
<p>2.&nbsp; Apply to be a Summer Science Fellow (deadline: January 14).&nbsp; See this <a href="http://serc.carleton.edu/cismi/broadaccess/summer_fellows.html">site</a> for details. &nbsp;</p>
<p>3.&nbsp; Apply through our general application process (deadline: February 1).&nbsp; The department sponsors a variable number of student researchers through various grants, including the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and the National Science Foundation.&nbsp; See below for details.</p>
<p><strong>Application Process</strong></p>
<p>To be eligible, you must be a current Carleton student (graduating seniors are not eligible).&nbsp; If you are interested, fill out this application.&nbsp; <strong>The deadline to apply is February 1, 2011</strong>.&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>[Clare Boothe Luce]Clare Boothe Luce Research Scholars Program</strong></p>
<p>The Department of Computer Science is proud to offer the Clare Boothe Luce Research Scholars Program, which supports undergraduate research projects in physics, astronomy, and computer science as well as cross-disciplinary research projects in computational physics, geophysics, biophysics, computational chemistry, and physical chemistry. The awards will be given annually to eight women in Computer Science and Physics &amp; Astronomy or related fields. Each recipient will be paid a stipend of $4300 for 10 weeks of summer research, with additional funds allotted for research expenses and travel to meetings to present results.&nbsp; The CBL Research Scholars will take part in cohort activities such as summer lunch meetings, presentation of a poster on their research at Carleton's annual poster session and participation in related CBL activities throughout the academic year following their summer research.</p>
<p>To be eligible, the applicant must be:</p>
<ul>
<li>Female interested in computer science, physics, astronomy or related fields.</li>
<li>U.S. Citizen</li>
<li>Preference is for 1st or 2nd year students</li>
</ul>
<p>Carleton students interested in applying should fill out the application. The application deadline is February 1, 2011.</p>
<p>Clare Boothe Luce, the widow of Henry R. Luce, was a playwright, journalist, U.S. Ambassador to Italy, and the first woman elected to Congress from Connecticut. She appreciated, however, that many women face obstacles in their chosen professions. By establishing this program, she sought to encourage women to enter, study, graduate, and teach in the sciences, engineering, and mathematics. More information can be found on the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.hluce.org/cblprogram.aspx">Luce Foundation website</a>.</p></div>

</div>
</div>


